The general solution to the Proca equation involves a massive vector field \( A^{
u} \) that satisfies the Klein-Gordon equation due to the mass term \( m^2 \). The solution can be expressed in terms of plane waves:

\[ A^{
u}(x) = \epsilon^{
u}(p) e^{-ip \cdot x} \]

where \( \epsilon^{
u}(p) \) is the polarization vector satisfying the Lorenz condition \( \partial_{
u} A^{
u} = 0 \), and \( p \) is the four-momentum vector satisfying the dispersion relation \( p^2 = m^2 \). The polarization vector must also satisfy the transversality condition \( p_{
u} \epsilon^{
u}(p) = 0 \). The general solution is a superposition of such plane wave solutions.

